/-!
# Pointwise operations on filters

This file defines pointwise operations on filters. This is useful because usual algebraic operations
distribute over pointwise operations. For example,
* `(f‚āĀ * f‚āā).map m = f‚āĀ.map m * f‚āā.map m`
* `ūĚďĚ (x * y) = ūĚďĚ x * ūĚďĚ y`

## Main declarations

* `0` (`Filter.instZero`): Pure filter at `0 : őĪ`, or alternatively principal filter at `0 : Set őĪ`.
* `1` (`Filter.instOne`): Pure filter at `1 : őĪ`, or alternatively principal filter at `1 : Set őĪ`.
* `f + g` (`Filter.instAdd`): Addition, filter generated by all `s + t` where `s ‚ąą f` and `t ‚ąą g`.
* `f * g` (`Filter.instMul`): Multiplication, filter generated by all `s * t` where `s ‚ąą f` and
  `t ‚ąą g`.
* `-f` (`Filter.instNeg`): Negation, filter of all `-s` where `s ‚ąą f`.
* `f‚ĀĽ¬Ļ` (`Filter.instInv`): Inversion, filter of all `s‚ĀĽ¬Ļ` where `s ‚ąą f`.
* `f - g` (`Filter.instSub`): Subtraction, filter generated by all `s - t` where `s ‚ąą f` and
  `t ‚ąą g`.
* `f / g` (`Filter.instDiv`): Division, filter generated by all `s / t` where `s ‚ąą f` and `t ‚ąą g`.
* `f +ŠĶ• g` (`Filter.instVAdd`): Scalar addition, filter generated by all `s +ŠĶ• t` where `s ‚ąą f` and
  `t ‚ąą g`.
* `f -ŠĶ• g` (`Filter.instVSub`): Scalar subtraction, filter generated by all `s -ŠĶ• t` where `s ‚ąą f`
  and `t ‚ąą g`.
* `f ‚ÄĘ g` (`Filter.instSMul`): Scalar multiplication, filter generated by all `s ‚ÄĘ t` where
  `s ‚ąą f` and `t ‚ąą g`.
* `a +ŠĶ• f` (`Filter.instVAddFilter`): Translation, filter of all `a +ŠĶ• s` where `s ‚ąą f`.
* `a ‚ÄĘ f` (`Filter.instSMulFilter`): Scaling, filter of all `a ‚ÄĘ s` where `s ‚ąą f`.

For `őĪ` a semigroup/monoid, `Filter őĪ` is a semigroup/monoid.
As an unfortunate side effect, this means that `n ‚ÄĘ f`, where `n : ‚Ąē`, is ambiguous between
pointwise scaling and repeated pointwise addition. See note [pointwise nat action].

## Implementation notes

We put all instances in the scope `Pointwise`, so that these instances are not available by
default. Note that we do not mark them as reducible (as argued by note [reducible non-instances])
since we expect the scope to be open whenever the instances are actually used (and making the
instances reducible changes the behavior of `simp`).

## Tags

filter multiplication, filter addition, pointwise addition, pointwise multiplication,
-/

@[expose] public section


